				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Celius wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">For this reason it's good to have a tempo that's easily adjustable. And in NTSC songs you'll want to make it so the tempo is not at max speed (at max 5/6 of max speed so you can convert it to PAL). I'm not quite sure what you're doing for tempo, but I have a system where I specify one byte as the tempo. Each frame, it is added to itself, and if there's a wrap around, there's a tick. All note lengths are measured in these "ticks". So if you have the tempo set at $A0, it would look like this:<br /><br />Frame 0: $A0 + $A0 = $40 (tick)<br />Frame 1: $40 + $A0 = $E0 (no tick)<br />Frame 2: $E0 + $A0 = $80 (tick)<br />Frame 3: $80 + $A0 = $20 (tick)<br />Frame 4: $20 + $A0 = $C0 (no tick)<br /><br /><br />See in some frames, there isn't a tick, so there aren't 60 ticks a second. (There are actually 37.5). So you can raise this value to be higher so that it ticks more often:<br /><br />Tempo = $FF<br /><br />Frame 0: $FF + $FF = $FE (tick)<br />Frame 1: $FE + $FF = $FD (tick)<br />Frame 2: $FD + $FF = $FC (tick)<br /><br />Though you'd only want to use tempo $FF in PAL mode, because otherwise you couldn't adjust it from NTSC to PAL to be faster.<br /><br />Which brings me to my point. What you'd want to do is for NTSC have a max tempo of $D5 (5/6 of 256). This tempo will give you 50 ticks a second on NTSC, which is what $FF will give you on PAL mode. If you follow those guidelines, once you want to convert it to PAL, you can just multiply the tempo by 6/5.<br /><br />I think Bregalad is the one who suggested this method of timing to me. It's actually quite clever, I think.</div>
<br />
<br />Dude, you've accidentally helped me out a lot again!  I had some question marks in my sound notes - had very little idea what was going on with certain values - and now I know what they are!  It now appears to me that The Guardian Legend uses this same method to keep tempo for its music.  Only they don't seem to keep PAL much in mind because the intro song (the one I've been tracing) adds #$DE every frame <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" />.  I'd like to check the PAL version of the game to see if there is a little bit of slowdown in the song (I think there must be).
<br />
<br />Anyway, this was the missing piece of the puzzle for me and now I think I've finally cracked TGL's music format (minus a few effect-related details).  Thank you sir!</div>

