	<tr class="row2">

			<td align="center" valign="middle">
				<a name="p43596"></a>
				<b class="postauthor">Disch</b>
			</td>
			<td width="100%" height="25">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
				<tr>
				
					<td class="gensmall" width="100%"><div style="float: left;">&nbsp;<b>Post subject:</b> <a href="#p43596"></a></div><div style="float: right;"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=43596#p43596"><img src="./styles/subsilver2/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a><b>Posted:</b> Sun Feb 22, 2009 8:06 pm&nbsp;</div></td>
				</tr>
				</table>
			</td>
		</tr>

		<tr class="row2">

			<td valign="top" class="profile">
				<table cellspacing="4" align="center" width="150">
			
				<tr>
					<td><img src="./styles/subsilver2/imageset/en/icon_user_offline.gif" alt="Offline" title="Offline" /></td>
				</tr>
			
				<tr>
					<td><img src="./download/file.php?avatar=33.png" width="65" height="75" alt="User avatar" /></td>
				</tr>
			
				</table>

				<span class="postdetails">
					<br /><b>Joined:</b> Wed Nov 10, 2004 6:47 pm<br /><b>Posts:</b> 1670
				</span>

			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">But the formula you showed before, (60*60) / (120*4), also results in 7.5 for the 16th note, which will get truncated anyway</div><br /><br />Yes but they'll all be truncated, not just the 16th note.  What will end up happening is:<br />16th = 7<br />8th = 14<br />quarter = 28<br />etc<br /><br />instead of:<br />16th = 7 (7.5 truncated)<br />8th = 15<br />quarter = 30<br />etc<br /><br />This results in a slightly faster tempo than what you actually request, but it would probably go unnoticed (128.6 bpm instead of 120 bpm -- that's like nothing).  If you need really accurate precision for whatever reason (like that one guy who made that metronome program), then you definately would not want this approach.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">OK, if the shortest note I'll be playing is a 16th note, somehow I have to make it last 7.5 frames (if the tempo is 120 bpm). How the hack do I do that?</div><br /><br />If you need <em>exactly</em> 120 bpm then you'll need to do something like Celius' approach where one 'tick' does not necessarily have to be evenly divisible by a frame.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Anyway, I actually need more resolution than that for effects like volume envelopes, vibratos and that kind of thing. It just sounds impossible to make those things sound the same in 60fps and 50fps.</div>
<br />
<br />You would decay and vibratto probably on a frame-based timer, not on the tempo timer (ie:  the tempo likely wouldn't affect the speed of vibratto/volume change).  So 60Hz (or even 50Hz) is plenty fast enough.
<br />
<br />I had a semi-solution to this that I never actually tried.  The idea was similar to Celius' idea, but compounded.  Basically every frame you add N to a counter, and when it wraps, you have volume and everything take 1 step, and you also add M to the tempo, and when that wraps, you decrement note lengths and whatnot.
<br />
<br />So it's basically exactly the same as Celius' idea, only its two stages.  The tempo (M) wouldn't need to be changed for NTSC/PAL, but instead the rate (N) would change.
<br />
<br />Of course this is a little extreme, and is probably pretty computation heavy.
<br />
<br />Another, possibly more reasonable approach would be to do a variation of my tempo idea and use different LUTs for NTSC/PAL, rather than trying to do the computations at runtime.  Rather than saying "wait 5 frames between volume changes", you can say "wait 5 units between volume changes", and look up 5 units in a LUT (which could be 5 frames on PAL, but 6 frames on NTSC).</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

