				<span class="postdetails">
					<br /><b>Joined:</b> Sun Sep 19, 2004 11:12 pm<br /><b>Posts:</b> 9048<br /><b>Location:</b> NE Indiana, USA (NTSC)
				</span>

			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">This music stuff is harder than I though it would be. I know very little music theory, but since I'm a computer guy I figured that if I studied how the NES handles music I'd be looking at it in a language I understand. You guys still talk about whole notes, quarter notes, tempo... that stuff doesn't mean much to me</div><br />A lot of domains of human endeavor have few software choices because there are few programmers who also know the domain. That's why there isn't a lot of open-source CAD software: there aren't a lot of people who know both drafting and programming. In your case, you don't know both music and programming.<br /><br />In a tracker, a "whole note" is 96 underlying ticks of a tracker's time base.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I've also been studying some of it with FamiTracker, and I can't exactly tell why it has a "speed" setting if it already has a "tempo" setting.</div><br />"Speed" in a tracker tells how many 96th notes are in one row. For example, if one row is a 16th note, speed is 6, and trackers tend to come preset to speed=6. Or if it's a 12th note (8th note triplets), speed is 8.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I also didn't find anything in it about note durations whatsoever. Do different durations need different instruments by any chance?</div><br />Note durations in a tracker are multiples of a row. For example, if you have a note every 2 rows, and a row is a 16th note, each note is an 8th note long. (Exception: SCx and SDx effects, which delay a note-off or note-on respectively by x 96th notes.)<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">OK, if the shortest note I'll be playing is a 16th note, somehow I have to make it last 7.5 frames (if the tempo is 120 bpm). How the heck do I do that?</div><br />The tempo is 120 quarter notes per minute, or 480 rows per minute. Every frame, add the rows-per-minute value (here 480) to a 16-bit counter, and when that exceeds the platform's frame rate (3,000 fpm for PAL NES or 3,606 fpm for NTSC NES), subtract the frame rate from the counter and go to the next row in the pattern. You'll end up in a pattern of 7, 8, 7, 8, ... on NTSC.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"> Anyway, I actually need more resolution than that for effects like volume envelopes, vibratos and that kind of thing. It just sounds impossible to make those things sound the same in 60fps and 50fps.</div>
<br />If you want them to sound exactly the same, you'll probably have to make separate envelopes, or just double-clock the envelopes every fifth frame on PAL.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

